before large empires like Akkad or Babylon, Mesopotamia was a patchwork of independent city-states, each with its own ruler, military, and cultural achievements. Some were very influential but never controlled vast territories, so theyâ€™re usually not called â€œempires.â€ Hereâ€™s a list of the most important ones:

Key Mesopotamian City-States (Not Empires)
City-State	Approx. Dates	Notable Features / Rulers
Uruk	c. 4000â€“3100â€¯BCE	One of the worldâ€™s first cities; epic of Gilgamesh; early writing (cuneiform) and monumental architecture (temples, walls).
Kish	c. 3100â€“2500â€¯BCE	Often mentioned as the first city with kings after the Sumerian â€œfloodâ€; known for its temporary hegemony over other Sumerian cities.
Ur	c. 3800â€“2000â€¯BCE	Major trade center; famous Ziggurat of Ur; home of Ur-Nammu (later Ur III Empire founder).
Lagash	c. 2500â€“2100â€¯BCE	Militarily powerful; Eannatum extended influence regionally; rich archives of administrative tablets.
Nippur	c. 2500â€“1500â€¯BCE	Religious capital of Sumer; home of the main temple of Enlil; important spiritual authority.
Eridu	c. 5400â€“600â€¯BCE	Considered the â€œfirst cityâ€ in Sumerian tradition; associated with the god Enki.
Larsa	c. 2000â€“1763â€¯BCE	Gained prominence after Ur III; influential under King Rim-Sin; rival to Babylon.
Isin	c. 2017â€“1794â€¯BCE	Another Ur III successor; sometimes controlled southern Mesopotamia before Babylonian dominance.


Why they arenâ€™t considered empires:

Limited territorial control: They ruled their city and surrounding villages, but not multiple regions or peoples.

Short-lived hegemony: Some cities temporarily dominated neighbors (like Kish or Lagash), but not for centuries or across large distances.

Independent governance: No permanent centralized bureaucracy spanning multiple cities.

âœ… Summary:
These city-states were the building blocks of Mesopotamian civilization. Their competition, alliances, and trade networks set the stage for Akkad to unify them into the first empire.



-----------------------------------

After the fall of the Akkadian Empire, Mesopotamia splintered into several smaller empires, dynasties, and city-states, some of which were influential regionally but never grew to the scale of Akkad or later Babylon/Assyria.

Hereâ€™s a detailed list:

Minor Empires / Regional Powers After Akkad
Name	Dates	Notes
Gutian Dynasty	c. 2154â€“2112â€¯BCE	Gutians from the Zagros Mountains took control after Akkad collapsed. Considered a â€œforeignâ€ ruling period, less centralized, short-lived.
Neo-Sumerian / Ur III	2112â€“2004â€¯BCE	Founded by Ur-Nammu; last Sumerian empire; centralized bureaucracy; extended authority over southern Mesopotamia (Ur, Uruk, Lagash). Technically a major empire but smaller than Akkad in geographic scope.
Isin	2017â€“1794â€¯BCE	Successor city-state after Ur III; controlled southern Mesopotamia; rival to Larsa; culturally significant.
Larsa	2000â€“1763â€¯BCE	Regional power in southern Mesopotamia; briefly more powerful than Isin under Rim-Sin.
Elamite Dynasties (Susa / Anshan)	c. 2300â€“1600â€¯BCE	Neighboring region in southwestern Iran; periodically invaded Mesopotamia; controlled parts of the east.
Mari	c. 2900â€“1761â€¯BCE	Important trade city on the Euphrates; temporarily exerted influence over Syria and northern Mesopotamia; known for archives of royal letters.
Ebla (in Syria)	c. 2500â€“1600â€¯BCE	Regional kingdom; traded with Mari and Sumer; culturally influential but geographically separate from core Mesopotamia.
Kassite Babylon	1595â€“1155â€¯BCE	Controlled Babylon after Old Babylonian collapse; stabilized the region for centuries.
Mitanni / Hurrian Kingdom	c. 1500â€“1300â€¯BCE	Northern Mesopotamia / Syria; sometimes influential in the region, rivaling Assyria temporarily.



Key Points

After Akkad fell, Mesopotamia fragmented into city-states and regional powers (Isin, Larsa, Mari).

Some â€œminor empiresâ€ like Ur III or Kassite Babylon had strong administration and military control but didnâ€™t dominate as broadly as Akkad or Assyria.

Neighboring states like Elam, Mari, and Ebla sometimes influenced Mesopotamia without being â€œcore Mesopotamian empires.â€

This period of fragmentation is what allowed Babylon under Hammurabi to rise later and unify the region again.

âœ… Summary:

Major post-Akkadian empire: Ur III

Regional powers / city-states: Isin, Larsa, Mari

Neighboring â€œminor empiresâ€: Elam, Ebla, Mitanni, Kassite Babylon



